It's all supposed to make the Brotherhood lean slightly more into individualism than the X-Men's strictly binary color schemes, and that's something I hope to carry over into my designs for the second Brotherhood.

Also, all my X-Men's uniforms are I-Pod white, and then they have a single secondary color. For the Brotherhood, gold plays the same role as the white in uniting all of the team's looks. However, there always TWO secondary colors- sometimes different shades of the same color. -> https://t.co/5EEl1onAOv

The Brotherhood's sense of fashion reveals that they don't give a shit what what humanity thinks about them. To give their costumes a sense of exoticism, I leaned into superhero fashion as hard as possible. Bright colors, huge shoulder pads, weird headgear... -> https://t.co/LnFL4MZmAq

Then there's the Brotherhood. I wanted them to look regal, but also very alien. I imagined them living on a version of Genosha with strange Jack Kirby architecture, far removed from humanity. -> https://t.co/vVBAHGjjvW

There's quite a bit of individuality going on with each outfit, but overall they're uniforms; a set. It's supposed to play into the idea that the X-Men believe humans and mutants can get along. It's mutant fashion, but toned down a bit so it's easier for humans to accept. -> https://t.co/D2ZDo4v3f5

Behind the scenes thread: I wanted my X-Men and Brotherhood redesigns to be communicated in two very distinct visual languages. The X-Men have this very futuristic look to their outfits. It evokes a sort of utopian look, but there's also a lot of... conformity going on there. -> https://t.co/urWrZdDIhy
